The City of Donna Wastewater Plant handles chlorine in amounts exceeding the regulatory threshold set by the EPA and by OSHA for regulated substances and the facility is managed by OMI, Inc., a private contractor, so the chlorination process is therefore subject to OSHA Process Safety Management (PSM) requirements (29 CFR 1910.119). The EPA threshold quantity is 2,500 pounds; the OSHA threshold quantity is 1,500 pounds.  The facility is subject to Prevention Program 3 of the Clean Air Act.
The offsite consequence analysis for the Wastewater Treatment Plant includes consideration of two release scenarios for chlorine.  
1. A Worst-Case Release
2. An Alternative Scenario

The following key elements outline the accidental release prevention program for the Donna Water Filtration Plant:

$    High level of training of the operators;
$    Preventive maintenance program;
$    Use of state-of-the-art process and safety equipment;
$    Use of accurate and effective operating procedures, written with the participation   of the operators;
$    Performance of a Process Hazard Analysis of equipment and procedures;
$    Implementation of an audit and inspection program.

As part of its Prevention Program 3, the Donna Wastewater Plant maintains an employee participation plan, Pre-startup Procedures, Hot Work Permit Procedures, Management of Change, and a procedure for contractors working at the facility, as well as an emergency plan and documents relating to operating procedures and employee training. 

Prevention steps include operator use of the available SCBA during connection/disconnection of the chemical supply, awareness of the hazardous and toxic properties of chlorine, and the presence of a chemical detector. Donna Water Treatment Plant management has an agreement with Chemical Response & Remediation Contractors, Inc. (CRRC) for assistance with emergency response.

